doc_1.content:
Thesis Statement
Can you boil the main idea of your essay down to just one sentence? If so, congratulations—you have a thesis statement! 

Your thesis statement is the most important item in your essay, so write it first and spend time early on making it strong.
A solid thesis statement keeps you focused as you write and helps the reader instantly understand the point you are trying to make. 
A weak or missing thesis statement spells disaster—you have no main idea to motivate or drive the paper, and you’re thus prone to go off in many divergent directions, leaving your reader confused and unfocused.

doc_2.content:
Thesis Statement Examples
From a paper about automotive entrepreneur Preston Tucker:
“Although Tucker’s unsound financial and marketing tactics, along with poor corporate governance, led to the swift downfall of his visionary automobile, Tucker had a lasting impact on the US auto industry that hastened performance and safety innovations that continue to benefit consumers long after his departure.”

doc_3.content:
Outline
Once you have a topic and a thesis statement, your next task should be to outline the paper in a very brief form. 

The basic outline consists of three parts: introduction, body, and conclusion. 

An outline can be very sparse at first (you can expand it later), and need only include your thesis statement and a list of arguments or points you will make in defense of it.  
When outlining, be sure that the structure of the paper conforms to the order of topics/ arguments laid out in the thesis statement and opening paragraphs (see example below)

doc_4.content:
Outline Example
Introduction: provide a catch/ hook to engage the reader (optional), then, most importantly, write out the THESIS STATEMENT!
    		 Thesis statement: “Although economists are divided on many points, most of them agree that economic prosperity for a 	country depends on factors A, B, and C.”
Paragraph 1: this paragraph is ALL ABOUT A, and nothing else! Address everything you think is important about item A.
	Topic sentence: "Item A is defined as... Item A is unique and important..." 
Paragraph 2: this paragraph is ALL ABOUT B, and nothing else--except for possibly relating B to A! Address everything you think is important about item B
	Topic sentence: "In addition to item A, economists consider item B as nearly as important... 
 	Follow-up topic sentences for more complex arguments: “The main features of item B are X, Y, and Z... Item B is influential 	on activity q..." 
Paragraph 3: this paragraph is ALL ABOUT C. Focus on a smooth TRANSITION from talking about A/B to talking about C. Again, only bring up items A and B in relation to C—if you have something extra to say about items A or B by themselves, that should go in paragraph 1 or 2 above. 
	Topic sentence: “Finally, economists consider the importance of item C… like/ unlike items A and B… Item C has a major 	impact on L, M, and P…
Conclusion/ summary: restate the thesis (in a more generalized form if possible) and BRIEFLY summarize EVERYTHING you addressed in the essay. Optional: you may also raise implications of your arguments for future research, public policy application, etc.
	Topic sentence “The success of our economy depends on the proper recognition of the effects of A, B, and C…

doc_5.content:
Topic Sentences
Next to a strong thesis, topic sentences are the most useful tool for good writing. Good topic sentences connect the ideas to each paragraph to each other and to your thesis, and keep the essay flowing steadily from point to point. 
Each paragraph should begin with a topic sentence—a sentence that lays out in brief form what the paragraph is about. Topic sentences should also contain “transition” language that connects the ideas in the current paragraph to the previous paragraph(s) and/or the general theme (thesis statement) of the entire essay.

doc_6.content:
Rewriting
Do you want to take your writing from adequate to excellent? There is no substitute for rewriting. 

Rewriting Tips
Wait at least a day between writing and rewriting—approach your project with fresh eyes and a calm mind.
Don’t be afraid to cut! Make every word, every sentence justify its place in your essay. Good writing is brief and to the point. 
Read your work aloud before rewriting—often errors or poor construction will appear more obvious in oral speech.

doc_7.content:
Style Guidelines
Good writing is as much an art as a science—there is no one right way to write so as to engage and persuade your reader. That being said, there are common pitfalls to avoid. While this list is not exhaustive, the following are some common stylistic problems to avoid.

doc_8.content:
Passive verb voice
Sentences are typically structured in subject-verb-object form. For example: “The dog crossed the road.” In this sentence the subject (the dog) does an action (crosses) to an object (the road). Passive construction flips the subject and object: “The road was crossed by the dog.” Passive verb voice is not inherently evil, but its overuse can cause clunky, ineffective writing. Passive voice should be avoided as much as possible—er, that is, avoid passive voice!

Example
Bad: “The bad effects of the tax hike could not be seen immediately.”  
Good: “The public did not immediately realize the harmful effects of the tax hike.”

doc_9.content:
1st or 2nd person verb usage
Use of first person (I, we) or second person (you) subject is not proper for formal, academic writing. Stick to third person, even if it sounds more awkward than the conversational tone of first or second person. 


Example
Bad: “I start with providing an overview of the monetary and fiscal policies used by the Fed, then I illustrate how they affect the economy.”   
Good: “This paper will start by providing an overview of the monetary and fiscal policies used by the Fed, then moves on to illustrate how they affect the economy.”

doc_10.content:
Comma Splices
Do use a comma:
When listing more than two items (bread, peanut butter, and jelly)
When joining a dependent to an independent clause (see slide 19 for more on clauses)
“Once we get there, you guys can set up the tent.”

Don’t use a comma:
When joining two independent clauses (use a semicolon or a conjunction)
“We are going to go; you all can do what you want.” 
“It’s raining outside and the game is delayed.” (Not “It’s raining outside, and the game is delayed.”)

doc_11.content:
Apostrophe Rules
Use an apostrophe ONLY:
To indicate possessive case of a noun. Apostrophe before the final s for singular nouns, after the final s for plural nouns.
“Hand me Mary’s backpack, please.”
“The lawyers’ lobby is very powerful in Washington.”
“Is that the Watts’ car?” (note: no extra s needed for a word that ends in s)
Exception: The 3rd person singular possessive pronoun its does not get an apostrophe
“The college has its own power plant.”

To mark out omitted words or letters from a contraction.
“That kid’s got talent.” (“That kid has got talent.”)
“It’s going to rain tonight.” (“It is going to rain tonight.”)
“There’s the place where we used to live.” (“There is the place where we used to live.”)

doc_12.content:
Number Agreement
Subject-Verb: singular subject, singular verb; plural subject, plural verb
Bad: “People does great work when they face strong incentives.” 
Good: “People do great work when they face strong incentives.”

Bad: “Each and every student are writing effectively. Each student love economics.”
Good: “Each and every student is writing effectively. Each student loves economics.”
Note: “Each and every” is just a modifier here; student is the subject, and it’s singular.

Noun-Pronoun: singular noun must take a singular pronoun; plural noun must take a plural pronoun
Bad: “Each student has their own writing style.” 
Good: “Each student has his own writing style.” [“his or her” or just “her” are also acceptable]
Note here the pronoun “his”/ “his or her” represents the singular noun “student.”

Bad: “We all have his or her own way of doing things.”
Good: “We all have our own way of doing things.”
Here the possessive pronoun “our” must match up in number and person (1st, 2nd, or 3rd) to subject pronoun “we.”

doc_13.content:
Pronouns and Antecedents
Pronouns must agree with their antecedents (the nouns for which pronouns “stand in”) in person, number (see p. 13) and case.

Wrong: “Each student should be careful when writing their essays”

Correct: “Each student should be careful when writing his or her essay”
Or:          “All students should be careful when writing their essays”

Antecedent references should be unambiguous. Avoid starting sentences with a pronoun, especially if there’s any chance the antecedent is unclear.

Wrong: It is the weakest part of the book.

Correct: The author’s claim about string theory is the weakest part of the book

doc_14.content:
Prepositions[note: every preposition on this page is highlighted in yellow]
Prepositions relate words to each other with respect to location, direction, position, time, etc. They are some of the most commonly used words in English and are thus subject to abuse. Here are some guidelines to follow in order to use prepositions well.
Avoid starting or ending sentences with prepositions.
Bad: “With economics knowledge people can make better decisions.”
Good: “Economics knowledge enables people to make better decisions.”
Bad: “In trading with other countries everybody can have more goods.”
Good: “International trade allows everybody to have more of everything.”
Bad: “He is fun to play tennis with.”
Good: “I enjoy playing tennis with him.”
Avoid over-use of prepositional phrases. 
A prepositional phrase is a preposition followed by its object, e.g. “on the house,” “inside the country,” “toward the end.” It is by no means wrong to use prepositional phrases, but careless use can make for clunky, unclear construction.
Bad: “Economics papers are better with writing that is clear and concise.” 
Good: “Clear, concise writing makes for better economics papers.”
Note here the elimination of the prepositional phrase, “with writing…” and the change of “writing” from the object of a prepositional phrase to the subject of the sentence.

doc_15.content:
Participles and Gerunds
Participles and gerunds are the –ing forms of verbs. They transform verb tense, as in present active participle (“He is running for President”) or transform verbs into nouns as in the gerund (“Running is my favorite hobby.”) There is nothing wrong with using participles or gerunds, but they are often used clumsily and avoiding them altogether can make sentences clearer and more concise.
Bad: “Free trade is allowing for countries having a higher standard of living.”
Good: “Free trade allows countries to have a higher standard of living.”

doc_16.content:
Participial Phrases and Dangling Participles
A participial phrase is simply a participle followed by its object: “Grading economics papers…” Such phrases are not inherently evil, but they can be easily misused. Avoid them whenever possible to enhance clarity.
Bad: “Going back to the thesis, economics teaches that prices are formed strictly by supply and demand, not by mere chance.”
Good: “As the thesis suggests, economics teaches that prices are formed by supply and demand and not merely by chance.”
Dangling participles are participial phrases that modify an absent subject: “Doing much better, we decided not to visit him in the hospital.” Who is doing better—the potential visitors, or the patient? In this case the participial phrase causes confusion and should be fixed or omitted. “He was recovering, so we decided not to visit him in the hospital.”
Bad: “Constantly running without shoes, it is obvious his feet would get sore.”
Good: “Running without shoes obviously made his feet constantly sore.”
Best: “He regularly ran without shoes, and thus his feet were always sore.”

doc_17.content:
Incomplete and Run-On Sentences
Every sentence must have a subject and a verb (“He runs.”); academic writing calls for clear subject-verb-object form (“He runs marathons.”). If a group of words lacks a subject or verb, it is not a sentence, but an “incomplete sentence.” (Incomplete sentences typically lack a verb rather than a subject. 
Incomplete: “Primarily, the overpaid executives without good morals.”
Sentence: “The main culprits were the unscrupulous, overpaid executives.” 
While there is no fixed limit on sentence length, sentences can easily become unclear if they run beyond 30 or 40 words. Keep sentences clear and concise by avoiding excessive use of dependent clauses and appositives (see next two slides)
Run-On: “With the lifting of the Iron Curtain the Soviets, who had ruled Eastern Europe in a harsh, dictatorial fashion, often spying on local citizens, locking up dissidents and even murdering political opponents, were forced to retreat leaving chaos and a political vacuum in their wake that had to be filled by the strongest local political organizations which the United States and its allies were attempting to help by funneling aid ranging from translated books on democracy to academics and policy experts who were flown in to help transitioning national governments form and create free, representative governments in these places which had formerly known only dictatorship and repression.”

doc_18.content:
Clauses
A clause is a semi-sentence—a group of words with a subject, verb, and object. Note: a group of words without a subject and verb is just a phrase: “The man upstairs” (subject, no verb); “Run for fun” (verb, no subject). There are two kinds of clauses:
Independent clause, which can stand alone as a complete sentence.
“The dishwasher was running.”
“He became President.”
Dependent clause, which cannot stand alone as a complete sentence. A dependent clause typically begins with a “subordinating conjunction” (if, when, because, etc.) and must be joined to an independent clause. 
“Because the dishwasher was running, the rest of us could not take a shower.”
“The economy entered into recession after he became President.” 
Joining Independent Clauses: Two independent clauses may be joined by the use of a semicolon or a conjunction such as and, because, therefore, so, etc. No comma or semicolon is needed when joining independent clauses by use of a conjunction
“He became President and the economy entered into recession.”

doc_19.content:
Slang, Idiom, and Argot
Avoid slang (informal terms and neologisms), idiomatic expressions that your target audience might not recognize, and argot—expressions known only to a particular group. Academic writing should be formal, clear, and accessible to anyone with a basic education.

Bad: “The alpha chi shindig was totes fab.”
Good: “The alpha chi party was very fun.”

Bad: “Curry was hugely impactful on the way the game was played.”
Good: “Curry exerted a strong influence on the way the game was played.”

Multinational Corporations
A multinational corporation (MNC) is a firm that has been incorporated in one country and has production and sales operations in other countries
Approximately 60,000 MNCs in the world with over 500,000 foreign affiliates
Benefit from the economy of scale in many ways:
Spreading R&D expenditures and advertising costs over their global sales
Pooling global purchasing power over suppliers
Utilizing their technological and managerial know-how globally with minimum additional costs

Corporate Governance
“Agency problem”: managers may pursue their own private interests at the expense of shareholders when they are not closely monitored
This “agency problem” is a major weakness of the public corporation
corporate governance: regulates the relationship between a firm’s management and its shareholders/ stakeholders
Institutions: laws, regulations, corporate structure
Be aware of differences across countries!
